00:28:43.992 --> 00:28:44.700
AUDIENCE: Thanks.

00:28:44.700 --> 00:28:45.100
Hi.

00:28:45.100 --> 00:28:46.141
ELIZABETH KOLBERT: Howdy.

00:28:46.141 --> 00:28:49.860
AUDIENCE: So you talked
about fossil fuel use.

00:28:49.860 --> 00:28:51.400
That seems to be the big issue.

00:28:51.400 --> 00:28:54.990
But there's also a lot happening
in the world moving away

00:28:54.990 --> 00:28:57.330
from fossil fuels.

00:28:57.330 --> 00:29:00.870
So first of all, are
there any other--

00:29:00.870 --> 00:29:04.620
we do a lot of other
stuff besides burn fuel.

00:29:04.620 --> 00:29:07.880
ELIZABETH KOLBERT: Yeah,
and we burn a lot of fuel.

00:29:07.880 --> 00:29:10.180
AUDIENCE: But is that sort
of a hopeful thing, that we

00:29:10.180 --> 00:29:14.424
are starting to use
more green energy?

00:29:14.424 --> 00:29:16.090
ELIZABETH KOLBERT:
It's a hopeful thing.

00:29:16.090 --> 00:29:21.430
But in terms of
actual numbers, we

00:29:21.430 --> 00:29:28.450
can go back to-- we're
using more renewable energy.

00:29:28.450 --> 00:29:30.390
We're also using
more fossil fuels.

00:29:30.390 --> 00:29:33.230
If you just look at
emissions trends,

00:29:33.230 --> 00:29:35.290
they're not leveling
out worldwide.

00:29:35.290 --> 00:29:37.220
They have leveled
out in the States.

00:29:37.220 --> 00:29:41.270
But worldwide, they are actually
tracking them, very high end.

00:29:41.270 --> 00:29:44.012
There are these scenarios
which people may or may not

00:29:44.012 --> 00:29:44.720
be familiar with.

00:29:44.720 --> 00:29:47.620
The Intergovernmental
Panel on Climate Change

00:29:47.620 --> 00:29:49.239
had these scenarios,
like this is

00:29:49.239 --> 00:29:50.780
what the future's
going to look like.

00:29:50.780 --> 00:29:54.000
Here's low emissions future,
here's a medium emissions

00:29:54.000 --> 00:29:55.920
future, here's a high
emissions future.

00:29:55.920 --> 00:29:59.500
We are tracking the
high emissions future.

00:29:59.500 --> 00:30:06.369
So until that graph levels
off-- on some level,

00:30:06.369 --> 00:30:07.910
I don't want to say
it doesn't matter

00:30:07.910 --> 00:30:09.240
if we're using more renewable.

00:30:09.240 --> 00:30:10.070
Obviously, it does.

00:30:10.070 --> 00:30:13.900
It's taking away from what that
trend line would look like.

00:30:13.900 --> 00:30:17.010
But until we turn
that around, we

00:30:17.010 --> 00:30:23.420
haven't really gotten a
handle on this problem.

00:30:23.420 --> 00:30:25.310
So I do think it's very hopeful.

00:30:25.310 --> 00:30:29.200
Obviously, look, if we
could convert our economy

00:30:29.200 --> 00:30:32.650
to not running on fossil
fuels, that would be huge.

00:30:32.650 --> 00:30:34.500
That would be making an impact.

00:30:34.500 --> 00:30:35.580
That really would be.

00:30:35.580 --> 00:30:40.740
But I don't see signs
that we're really

00:30:40.740 --> 00:30:44.640
on that kind of an actual
transformative course yet.

00:30:44.640 --> 00:30:46.490
How's that?

00:30:46.490 --> 00:30:48.080
And I'm not alone.

00:30:48.080 --> 00:30:49.750
It's not my pessimism.

00:30:49.750 --> 00:30:54.395
I don't think anyone see
signs of that at this point.

00:30:54.395 --> 00:30:56.020
AUDIENCE: I know this
was a short talk.

00:30:56.020 --> 00:30:57.811
You've talked a lot
about the carbon cycle.

00:30:57.811 --> 00:31:00.710
But do you also talk in
the book about nitrogen,

00:31:00.710 --> 00:31:02.697
some of the things that
agriculture is doing?

00:31:02.697 --> 00:31:05.030
ELIZABETH KOLBERT: I do not
get into the nitrogen cycle,

00:31:05.030 --> 00:31:06.670
but I could have.

00:31:06.670 --> 00:31:10.472
One of the kind of
interesting things--

00:31:10.472 --> 00:31:11.930
if you want to call
it interesting.

00:31:11.930 --> 00:31:13.638
I don't know what the
right adjective is.

00:31:13.638 --> 00:31:15.900
I could have chosen
different ways in which we're

00:31:15.900 --> 00:31:18.130
changing the world
on a planetary scale.

00:31:18.130 --> 00:31:22.440
And the nitrogen cycle
could have been one of them.

00:31:22.440 --> 00:31:26.280
We fix more nitrogen--
I don't know

00:31:26.280 --> 00:31:28.740
if people remember their
high school bio, once again.

00:31:28.740 --> 00:31:30.340
But you need to fix nitrogen.

00:31:30.340 --> 00:31:33.130
Plants can't use the
nitrogen from the air

00:31:33.130 --> 00:31:35.350
because it's bound
together in N2.

00:31:35.350 --> 00:31:39.380
So we need nitrogen-fixing
bacteria to transform nitrogen

00:31:39.380 --> 00:31:40.590
into a usable form.

00:31:40.590 --> 00:31:44.790
And when people figured
out-- early in this century,

00:31:44.790 --> 00:31:48.300
a German chemist figured out how
to take nitrogen from the air

00:31:48.300 --> 00:31:50.687
and convert it to
ammonia and fix nitrogen.

00:31:50.687 --> 00:31:52.770
And that was the beginning
of nitrogen fertilizer.

00:31:52.770 --> 00:31:54.670
It's exactly a
century ago, in fact.

00:31:54.670 --> 00:31:58.130
We just celebrated a century
of nitrogen fertilizer.

00:31:58.130 --> 00:32:02.020
We now fix more nitrogen than
all terrestrial ecosystems

00:32:02.020 --> 00:32:02.930
combined.

00:32:02.930 --> 00:32:06.550
That has huge, huge
impacts on living things.

00:32:06.550 --> 00:32:10.010
It's why, for example, we
have a dead zone every summer

00:32:10.010 --> 00:32:11.120
in the Gulf of Mexico.

00:32:11.120 --> 00:32:13.870
Because all that
fertilizer comes down

00:32:13.870 --> 00:32:15.625
the Mississippi River.

00:32:15.625 --> 00:32:16.760
It fertilizes the Gulf.

00:32:16.760 --> 00:32:18.170
You get these huge algae blooms.

00:32:18.170 --> 00:32:19.740
The algae dies.

00:32:19.740 --> 00:32:21.630
It drops to the bottom.

00:32:21.630 --> 00:32:24.430
And you have deoxygenated water.

00:32:24.430 --> 00:32:26.280
And dead zones are
increasing worldwide.

00:32:26.280 --> 00:32:29.890
And it's all a function of
nitrogen fertilizer runoff.

00:32:29.890 --> 00:32:31.574
So that would be
a whole other way

00:32:31.574 --> 00:32:33.115
that we could have
this conversation.

00:32:37.350 --> 00:32:39.780
AUDIENCE: Speaking
of agriculture,

00:32:39.780 --> 00:32:46.112
I read that even if we stopped
using fossil fuels for power,

00:32:46.112 --> 00:32:50.580
the agriculture that
we used to produce meat

00:32:50.580 --> 00:32:54.770
would still contribute more than
half of the greenhouse gases.

00:32:54.770 --> 00:32:57.740
But not carbon dioxide--
different ones.

00:32:57.740 --> 00:32:59.115
Is that accurate?

00:33:02.100 --> 00:33:04.305
ELIZABETH KOLBERT:
I don't think so.

00:33:04.305 --> 00:33:05.810
How's that?

00:33:05.810 --> 00:33:09.870
Our cows and things like
that are burping methane,

00:33:09.870 --> 00:33:10.450
for example.

00:33:10.450 --> 00:33:13.280
That's one way that
agriculture just produces CO2

00:33:13.280 --> 00:33:16.405
without actually
burning fossil fuels.

00:33:16.405 --> 00:33:18.030
But I think maybe
what you're referring

00:33:18.030 --> 00:33:22.130
to is studies have shown that
meat production in general,

00:33:22.130 --> 00:33:27.650
which is pretty fuel intensive
and pretty crop intensive,

00:33:27.650 --> 00:33:28.750
obviously.

00:33:28.750 --> 00:33:33.750
And also has these other
effects of methane emissions.

00:33:33.750 --> 00:33:36.840
They are a major
source of emissions.

00:33:36.840 --> 00:33:40.710
So a lot of people,
smart people,

00:33:40.710 --> 00:33:42.750
have sort of
advocated that we all

00:33:42.750 --> 00:33:45.340
eat either a lot
less meat or no meat.

00:33:45.340 --> 00:33:48.179
And that that would have
a significant impact

00:33:48.179 --> 00:33:48.720
on emissions.

00:33:48.720 --> 00:33:49.990
And I think it would.

00:33:49.990 --> 00:33:52.380
It's not going to
eliminate the problem,

00:33:52.380 --> 00:33:53.915
but it would have an impact.

00:33:56.700 --> 00:33:57.310
AUDIENCE: Hi.

00:33:57.310 --> 00:34:00.510
I'm wondering if you've
encountered a lot of climate

00:34:00.510 --> 00:34:03.290
change deniers or
human impact deniers.

00:34:03.290 --> 00:34:08.940
And if you have, what sort of
arguments have swayed them?

00:34:08.940 --> 00:34:13.900
ELIZABETH KOLBERT: Well,
climate change denial

00:34:13.900 --> 00:34:22.860
is such a weird sort of
counterfactual world.

00:34:22.860 --> 00:34:24.679
Here's a graph
showing you what's

00:34:24.679 --> 00:34:27.070
happening to CO2 levels
in the atmosphere.

00:34:27.070 --> 00:34:30.480
And if you know CO2's a
greenhouse gas-- which we know.

00:34:30.480 --> 00:34:32.920
We've known for
150 years-- and you

00:34:32.920 --> 00:34:35.770
know you're increasing it very
rapidly and very radically,

00:34:35.770 --> 00:34:38.440
you'd say, OK, well, I kind of
expect the world to warm up.

00:34:38.440 --> 00:34:40.900
So we just have these
ridiculous arguments,

00:34:40.900 --> 00:34:44.210
like it's cold in
New York this week.

00:34:44.210 --> 00:34:46.920
So there can be
no climate change.

00:34:46.920 --> 00:34:49.348
It's impossible.

00:34:49.348 --> 00:34:51.889
Much smarter people than I have
spent a lot of time thinking,

00:34:51.889 --> 00:34:56.130
how can you counter such
ridiculous arguments

00:34:56.130 --> 00:34:57.330
at this point?

00:34:57.330 --> 00:34:58.200
And it's very hard.

00:34:58.200 --> 00:35:00.270
I don't have the
answer for that.

00:35:00.270 --> 00:35:03.190
But in terms of
other human impacts,

00:35:03.190 --> 00:35:06.330
interestingly enough,
you very rarely

00:35:06.330 --> 00:35:11.580
hear people being ocean
acidification deniers.

00:35:11.580 --> 00:35:16.699
It's either too complicated
or it's just irrefutable.

00:35:16.699 --> 00:35:20.180
You increase CO2
levels in the air.

00:35:20.180 --> 00:35:22.010
Very basic chemistry
tells us you're

00:35:22.010 --> 00:35:26.250
going to be increasing carbon
dioxide levels in the oceans.

00:35:26.250 --> 00:35:27.470
We can measure it.

00:35:27.470 --> 00:35:28.610
We are measuring it.

00:35:28.610 --> 00:35:32.650
The pH of the surface waters
of the ocean is declining.

00:35:32.650 --> 00:35:35.350
It's pretty irrefutable.

00:35:35.350 --> 00:35:38.110
And once again,
the list goes on.

00:35:38.110 --> 00:35:40.810
We're obviously altering
the nitrogen cycle.

00:35:40.810 --> 00:35:44.440
It's not really
possible to deny that.

00:35:44.440 --> 00:35:49.010
So the weird way that we're sort
of fixated on climate change,

00:35:49.010 --> 00:35:53.140
yes or no, I think is
a complete function

00:35:53.140 --> 00:36:00.630
of a bunch of increasingly
embattled information sources,

00:36:00.630 --> 00:36:03.350
which have been funded by
all the usual suspects.

00:36:03.350 --> 00:36:07.460
All of that is
true that you read.

00:36:07.460 --> 00:36:08.020
AUDIENCE: Hi.

00:36:08.020 --> 00:36:10.730
Thanks for coming to
speak with us today.

00:36:10.730 --> 00:36:13.260
That picture of the
stark differences

00:36:13.260 --> 00:36:16.330
in what the ocean looks like is
almost enough to make someone

00:36:16.330 --> 00:36:17.360
want to cry.

00:36:17.360 --> 00:36:18.370
ELIZABETH KOLBERT:
Yeah, it should be.

00:36:18.370 --> 00:36:20.578
AUDIENCE: And I think there
are a lot of smart people

00:36:20.578 --> 00:36:22.360
who realize that
change is happening.

00:36:22.360 --> 00:36:25.990
But it feels so impossible
to make any change happen.

00:36:25.990 --> 00:36:29.950
And I guess my first
question to you would be,

00:36:29.950 --> 00:36:31.700
what could change things?

00:36:31.700 --> 00:36:33.980
But I guess, in thinking
about my question to you,

00:36:33.980 --> 00:36:37.190
it's more a question of do you
think there's anything that'll

00:36:37.190 --> 00:36:39.300
change this trajectory,
and what would that be.

00:36:39.300 --> 00:36:42.595
Because it feels almost like
an insurmountable issue.

00:36:45.660 --> 00:36:47.160
ELIZABETH KOLBERT: Yes.

00:36:47.160 --> 00:36:48.920
Yes, it does feel that way.

00:36:48.920 --> 00:36:52.810
I think one of the reasons
I'm glad to be here and then

00:36:52.810 --> 00:37:00.720
talking to you folks at
Google is because there are

00:37:00.720 --> 00:37:03.540
very smart people at Google who
are very aware of this problem

00:37:03.540 --> 00:37:09.100
and know what it takes for
transformative technologies

00:37:09.100 --> 00:37:13.770
to enter our world
and really change

00:37:13.770 --> 00:37:16.270
the way we think about things
and the way we do things.

00:37:16.270 --> 00:37:20.070
And I think that that
is one possibility.

00:37:20.070 --> 00:37:22.970
And there is one possibility--
some gentleman said

00:37:22.970 --> 00:37:27.960
before, there are renewable
sources of energy out there

00:37:27.960 --> 00:37:29.970
that are increasingly
being deployed.

00:37:29.970 --> 00:37:33.180
And that is true-- not
in a transformative way

00:37:33.180 --> 00:37:34.770
at this point.

00:37:34.770 --> 00:37:36.950
But it seems to
be not impossible

00:37:36.950 --> 00:37:40.800
that that could happen if very
smart engineers, like those

00:37:40.800 --> 00:37:42.890
at Google, put
their minds to it.

00:37:42.890 --> 00:37:44.960
It seems to me that
that is a possibility.

00:37:44.960 --> 00:37:48.190
I am not an engineer,
so I don't claim

00:37:48.190 --> 00:37:50.610
to know what that's going to be.

00:37:50.610 --> 00:37:55.110
But there are very, very,
very big forces at work here.

00:37:55.110 --> 00:37:57.590
There's 7.2 billion
people on the planet.

00:37:57.590 --> 00:38:01.840
A lot of people want to raise
their standard of living, which

00:38:01.840 --> 00:38:05.120
unfortunately right now tracks.

00:38:05.120 --> 00:38:08.420
Global GDP and global
carbon track each other.

00:38:08.420 --> 00:38:13.880
And until and unless we uncouple
those or decide to have a lower

00:38:13.880 --> 00:38:18.540
GDP, we're in this cycle
where emissions are just

00:38:18.540 --> 00:38:19.700
going to keep going up.

00:38:19.700 --> 00:38:21.490
Impacts are just going
to keep increasing.

00:38:21.490 --> 00:38:24.260
And I certainly
don't claim to have

00:38:24.260 --> 00:38:26.510
the answer of how we're going
to break that connection

00:38:26.510 --> 00:38:29.450
or if we're going to
break that connection.

00:38:29.450 --> 00:38:31.779
But it doesn't seem to
me impossible that that

00:38:31.779 --> 00:38:32.320
could happen.

00:38:35.610 --> 00:38:38.030
AUDIENCE: I'm curious
about-- besides

00:38:38.030 --> 00:38:41.860
domesticated and invasive
species, what kind

00:38:41.860 --> 00:38:45.520
of animals or species are
benefiting from human impact?

00:38:45.520 --> 00:38:51.380
And is that change in
scope or population count,

00:38:51.380 --> 00:38:54.210
is that a big effect relative
to the first-order effects

00:38:54.210 --> 00:38:55.689
of human impact?

00:38:55.689 --> 00:38:57.730
ELIZABETH KOLBERT: That's
a really good question.

00:38:57.730 --> 00:39:00.755
And I don't have a
great answer for that,

00:39:00.755 --> 00:39:02.380
but it's a really
interesting question.

00:39:06.370 --> 00:39:10.760
For example, rats seem
to do really well.

00:39:10.760 --> 00:39:16.749
All of the species that we know
benefit from human disturbance

00:39:16.749 --> 00:39:17.790
seemed to do really well.

00:39:17.790 --> 00:39:20.360
So rats have been taken
around the world by people.

00:39:20.360 --> 00:39:23.024
They are now on islands,
like the Hawaiian islands

00:39:23.024 --> 00:39:23.940
where they never were.

00:39:23.940 --> 00:39:27.090
The Hawaiian islands
had no mammals.

00:39:27.090 --> 00:39:30.340
They're on really
tiny distant islands

00:39:30.340 --> 00:39:34.479
in the Alaskan peninsula,
where people never

00:39:34.479 --> 00:39:35.270
bothered to settle.

00:39:35.270 --> 00:39:38.342
But they left rats behind.

00:39:38.342 --> 00:39:39.300
So rats are everywhere.

00:39:39.300 --> 00:39:41.400
And one of the guys
that I went out

00:39:41.400 --> 00:39:45.054
with in the book, a
British geologist, sort of

00:39:45.054 --> 00:39:46.720
speculated-- and it
was tongue in cheek,

00:39:46.720 --> 00:39:49.810
but only half tongue
in cheek-- that rats

00:39:49.810 --> 00:39:51.550
will inherit the
earth, that that

00:39:51.550 --> 00:39:55.442
will become a dominant group.

00:39:55.442 --> 00:39:57.400
But I think it is a really
interesting question

00:39:57.400 --> 00:39:59.280
because clearly, yes.

00:39:59.280 --> 00:40:02.680
Ecospace that's being
emptied by other species

00:40:02.680 --> 00:40:06.120
may or may not be being
taken up by species

00:40:06.120 --> 00:40:08.590
that benefit from
human disturbance.

00:40:08.590 --> 00:40:11.210
It's not clear that your
